According to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Wannerton"><font face="Arial" size="2" color="#0645AD">James Wannerton</font></a>, "Whenever I hear, read, or articulate (inner speech) words or word sounds, I experience an immediate and involuntary taste sensation on my tongue. Even though at those times I intuatively attributed that to be a positive aspect, lately I have been thinking a lot about it. For example, writings encouraging revolts or construction of weapons can be of no benefit to our people; it is for this reason that we punish the creators of the offensive content. It should not be found objectionable that we would imprison a man attempting to rally support for a revolution online. However, should cyberspace be adapted as a Common Heritage of Mankind, Algeria may well lose its ability to punish people who stir civil unrest through the internet. Declaring cyberspace as a Common Heritage of Mankind would mean that an internationally defined set of laws would apply to the internet; however, if these laws disagree with Algerian law, citizens would be able to circumvent Algerian law by taking action through the internet. Such a large legal hole could be devastating to any countries that disagree with the newly set international laws, and could catalyze the loss of governmental control in these countries. Algeria must retain control of its internet functions within its borders.'</font></td></tr>
